# NestJS Standards — `apps/api`

## Architecture
- One module per domain feature. Never put business logic in `AppModule`.
- Layer order: **Controller → Service → (Repository/Prisma)**. Controllers handle HTTP only; services own all logic.
- Inject dependencies via constructor — never `new MyService()`.
- Bootstrap port from `process.env.PORT ?? 3001` (already set in `main.ts`).

## Modules
```ts
// ✅ Feature module structure
@Module({
  imports: [TypeOrmModule.forFeature([User])],
  controllers: [UsersController],
  providers: [UsersService],
  exports: [UsersService],
})
export class UsersModule {}
```

## DTOs & Validation
- Every controller input must be a DTO decorated with `class-validator`.
- Enable `ValidationPipe` globally in `main.ts` with `whitelist: true, forbidNonWhitelisted: true`.

```ts
export class CreateUserDto {
  @IsEmail()
  email: string

  @IsString()
  @MinLength(2)
  name: string
}
```

## Error Handling
- Throw NestJS built-in exceptions (`NotFoundException`, `BadRequestException`, etc.) from services.
- Never throw plain `Error` objects in controllers or services.

```ts
// ✅
const user = await this.usersService.findOne(id)
if (!user) throw new NotFoundException(`User ${id} not found`)
```

## TypeScript
- `experimentalDecorators` and `emitDecoratorMetadata` are enabled — required for NestJS decorators.
- Never use `any`; use `unknown` and narrow with type guards.
- All async functions must return typed `Promise<T>`.

## File Naming
```
users/
  users.module.ts
  users.controller.ts
  users.service.ts
  dto/create-user.dto.ts
  dto/update-user.dto.ts
  entities/user.entity.ts
```

## Testing
- Unit tests live alongside source files (`*.spec.ts`).
- E2E tests live in `apps/test/` (`*.e2e-spec.ts`).
- Mock all external dependencies in unit tests using `jest.fn()` or NestJS `createMock`.
